  "text": "Determination of Flux Constants. Differences in the timedependent uptake curves can be evaluated in terms of flux constants (Table I) based on a two-compartment model of medium and intracellular fluid [CITATION_1] . There was an age-dependent increase in both the net AMG flux and the fractional influx rate constant (AIM) with the adult values being slightly higher than the 3-month-old and nearly twice the newborn values. This was reflected in the age-dependent increase in the DR after I min of incubation. The fractional effiux rate constants showed a somewhat different pattern in that the highest value was observed with 3-month-old tubules, being 3-fold greater than newborn and 1.4-fold greater than the adult value. The newborn fractional effiux rate constant was the lowest value determined being only onehalf that of the adult . Because of the low fractional effiux rate constant, the newborn tubules achieved a steady-state DR comparable to the adult in spite of a low fractional influx rate constant. The high fractional effiux rate constant led to the low steady-state DR observed in the 3-month-old.",
